%description:
Regression test for CSPF path computation at the RSVP-TE ingress (Workstream C6):
~RsvpTe.computeEro (default off) makes the ingress compute a full strict ERO via
~Ted::calculateShortestPath() -- previously DEAD code (zero callers since 2005) -- whenever
a path's configured route is empty or all-loose.

Ad hoc DIAMOND: LSR1 -> {LSR2, LSR3} -> LSR4, no hosts (the tunnels terminate at LSR4
itself; endpoint = "LSR4%routerId"). The LSR1-LSR2-LSR4 branch is 600 kbps end to end and
the cheaper route by metric (LSR1-LSR2 metric 1, LSR2-LSR4 metric 1, total 2); the
LSR1-LSR3-LSR4 branch is 10 Mbps end to end and the more expensive route by metric
(LSR1-LSR3 metric 5, LSR3-LSR4 metric 5, total 10). All four LSRs have computeEro=true.

Scenario:
  1. At t=0, tunnel 1 (lspid 100, 500 kbps, permanent) is set up from the static traffic.xml.
     With both branches fully free, CSPF picks the plain-shortest (by metric) LSR2 branch --
     documented here as "which branch CSPF picks first" per the plan (the low-bandwidth
     branch happens to also be the low-metric one in this topology; that is a deliberate
     choice of this test's metrics, not a general property of CSPF).
  2. At t=2s (after tunnel 1 has fully established, including the CAC reservation on BOTH of
     its hops), a scenario add-session brings up tunnel 2 (lspid 200, another 500 kbps,
     permanent). The LSR1-LSR2 and LSR2-LSR4 links now have only 100 kbps free at priority 7
     (600k - 500k already reserved by tunnel 1) -- not enough for another 500k -- so CSPF's
     bandwidth pruning must exclude the entire LSR2 branch and route tunnel 2 via LSR3
     instead, even though LSR3 is the higher-metric, "naturally worse" branch.

Asserted: the EV_DETAIL line RsvpTe::createIngressPSB logs at the point it installs a
CSPF-computed ERO into the PSB (verbatim, see below), once for each tunnel, showing tunnel
1 via LSR2 (10.1.2.1) and tunnel 2 via LSR3 (10.1.4.1) specifically.

Falsification (performed manually while developing this test, as specified by the plan):
temporarily stubbed the CSPF call in createIngressPSB to always call
tedmod->calculateShortestPath(dest, tedmod->getLinks(), 0.0 /* stub: ignore requested
bandwidth */, session.sobj.setupPri, path.includeAny, path.excludeAny) -- i.e. the plain,
UNPRUNED shortest path, ignoring path.tspec.req_bandwidth entirely. Re-ran this exact test:
it FAILED -- tunnel 2's computed ERO line showed "10.1.2.1, 10.1.4.2" (the LSR2 branch,
identical to tunnel 1's), i.e. both tunnels piled onto the already-full LSR2 branch, and
the not-contains check below (which guards against exactly that) failed. Restored the
real pruning-aware call (path.tspec.req_bandwidth instead of the stubbed 0.0) and re-ran:
PASS again, confirming the bandwidth-pruning is actually load-bearing here, not vacuous.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: CspfDiamond.ned

import inet.common.scenario.ScenarioManager;
import inet.node.mpls.RsvpMplsRouter;

//
// Ad hoc diamond: LSR1 -> {LSR2 (600 kbps branch), LSR3 (10 Mbps branch)} -> LSR4.
// No hosts -- both tunnels terminate at LSR4 itself.
//
network CspfDiamond
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    submodules:
        LSR1: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=200,200");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR2: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,100");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR3: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,300");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR4: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=600,200");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        scenarioManager: ScenarioManager {
            @display("p=100,100;is=s");
        }
    connections:
        LSR1.pppg[0] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg[0];
        LSR2.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg[0];
        LSR3.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[1];
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Addressing: LSR1.ppp0=10.1.1.1 <-> LSR2.ppp0=10.1.1.2 (600k branch, hop A)
%#             LSR2.ppp1=10.1.2.1 <-> LSR4.ppp0=10.1.2.2 (600k branch, hop B)
%#             LSR1.ppp1=10.1.3.1 <-> LSR3.ppp0=10.1.3.2 (10M branch, hop A)
%#             LSR3.ppp1=10.1.4.1 <-> LSR4.ppp1=10.1.4.2 (10M branch, hop B)
%# routerId="auto" picks the HIGHEST interface address per LSR:
%#   LSR1 = max(10.1.1.1, 10.1.3.1) = 10.1.3.1
%#   LSR2 = max(10.1.1.2, 10.1.2.1) = 10.1.2.1
%#   LSR3 = max(10.1.3.2, 10.1.4.1) = 10.1.4.1
%#   LSR4 = max(10.1.2.2, 10.1.4.2) = 10.1.4.2
%# Metrics are set explicitly (see "Metric:" below) so the LSR2 branch is the cheaper one
%# by metric (1+1=2) and the LSR3 branch the more expensive one (5+5=10), independent of
%# any bandwidth-derived default metric.
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.3.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.3.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.4.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.4.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR1_rsvp.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<sessions>
	<session>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>

		<paths>
			<path>
				<lspid>100</lspid>
				<bandwidth>500000</bandwidth>
				<permanent>true</permanent>
			</path>
		</paths>
	</session>
</sessions>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: scenario.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<scenario>
	<at t="2s">
		<add-session module="LSR1.rsvp">
			<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
			<tunnel_id>2</tunnel_id>

			<paths>
				<path>
					<lspid>200</lspid>
					<bandwidth>500000</bandwidth>
					<permanent>true</permanent>
				</path>
			</paths>
		</add-session>
	</at>
</scenario>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = CspfDiamond
sim-time-limit = 3s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
%# only the rsvp modules log (at detail level, so the CSPF-computed-ERO EV_DETAIL line is
%# captured); keeping the log scoped avoids test.out bloat. NOTE: per-module cmdenv-log-level
%# overrides are matched in FILE ORDER (first matching pattern wins), so the specific
%# override MUST be declared before the general catch-all below.
**.LSR*.rsvp.cmdenv-log-level = detail
**.cmdenv-log-level = off

**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"
**.LSR4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR4.rt"

**.LSR1.rsvp.traffic = xmldoc("LSR1_rsvp.xml")
**.LSR*.rsvp.computeEro = true

**.LSR*.rsvp.helloInterval = 0.2s
**.LSR*.rsvp.helloTimeout = 0.5s

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

*.*.hasStatus = true
**.scenarioManager.script = xmldoc("scenario.xml")

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Sanity: the add-session at t=2s actually reached the ingress.
%contains: stdout
adding new session into database
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Tunnel 1 (lspid 100): both branches free, CSPF picks the lower-metric LSR2 branch
%# (LSR2's routerId 10.1.2.1, then LSR4's routerId 10.1.4.2).
%contains: stdout
CSPF computed ERO for session (dest=10.1.4.2, lspid=100): 10.1.2.1, 10.1.4.2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Tunnel 2 (lspid 200): the LSR2 branch is out of bandwidth at priority 7 (600k - 500k
%# already reserved by tunnel 1 on BOTH its hops), so CSPF's bandwidth pruning forces the
%# LSR3 branch (LSR3's routerId 10.1.4.1, then LSR4's routerId 10.1.4.2) -- the point of
%# this test.
%contains: stdout
CSPF computed ERO for session (dest=10.1.4.2, lspid=200): 10.1.4.1, 10.1.4.2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Both tunnels actually establish end to end (ingress PATH_CREATED confirmation), i.e. the
%# CSPF-computed EROs above are not just logged but actually signaled successfully. (Tunnel
%# 1's very FIRST CSPF attempt, at t=0 before LinkStateRouting's flooding has reached LSR4's
%# link from LSR1, legitimately finds no path yet and logs "CSPF found no feasible path" --
%# that is correct, expected behavior, not asserted against; the retry machinery, unchanged
%# by this commit, re-attempts it and succeeds once flooding converges, see the ERO line
%# above.)
%contains: stdout
Path successfully established
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Negative check tied to the falsification above: tunnel 2 must NOT end up on the LSR2
%# branch (which is exactly what happens if the bandwidth-pruning silently degenerates into
%# the plain unpruned shortest path).
%not-contains: stdout
CSPF computed ERO for session (dest=10.1.4.2, lspid=200): 10.1.2.1, 10.1.4.2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
